        "text": "Finally, abduction is a term introduced by the logician Charles S. Peirce to explain the formation of hypotheses and thereby solve the problem of logical closure, which prevents the \"penetration\" of the new. For logic cannot build a bridge from the world of ideas to the world of empirical experience by deduction from axioms alone. Abduction, therefore, infers a working hypothesis from an unknown case or phenomenon by forming a \"spontaneous rule.\" Again, this method is not a logical method of reasoning, but an intuitive one.\nDescriptions like these, applied to unobservable processes in the brain, are of course only descriptions of an observer describing a behavior. They are therefore metaphorical rather than scientific - with the caveat that scientific models are fundamentally metaphors. What exactly happens under our skullcap and how, remains in principle in the dark. Our descriptions are always only attempts to find a metaphor or to invent a mechanism that we can then reconstruct. Logic itself is also such a mechanism ...\nLogic is a basically conservative and at the same time hermetic method. A \"logic of innovation\" can therefore not primarily follow the laws of logic. Moreover, an innovation can only be recognized as such if one separates at least to some extent from the old view of things. However, this separation can only be made if one has retained one's curiosity, i.e. if one is prepared to look at things that do not fit into the grid of established theories, rules and principles."
